It is seen from Fig. 4
that compared to the ordinary Raman spectrum in solution, most of the SERS bands become a little broader and frequency-shift. The Raman bands at 1264 and 1464 cm−1 shows very strong enhancement (the Cartesian displacements shows in Fig. 5
). The intense bands at 1413, 1438, 1506, 1558, 1591 cm−1 in the SERS spectrum are similar to the bands of the ordinary Raman spectrum, and the bands show strong enhancement and frequency-shift with respect to the ordinary Raman spectrum of Tinuvin P solution. The bands at 1291 and 1335 cm−1 are the overlapping of two ordinary Raman bands, respectively, with little frequency-shift and strong enhancement. As demonstrated in Fig. 4, the relative intensities of SERS bands at 892, 967 and 989 cm−1 are similar to those of the ordinary Raman spectrum, and no frequency-shifts upon adsorption were observed. These spectral differences were induced by the interaction between the substrate of template-embedded gold array and the Tinuvin P adsorbate, which may considerably alter the polarizability tensor of the Tinuvin P molecule [42].
